message.content:
A Turdus viscivorus is a species commonly known as the mistle thrush.
It has a plump and sturdy body with a length of about 27-30 cm and a wingspan of around 42-47 cm.
Its back and wings have a brownish-grey color with a spotted pattern, while its underparts are off-white with darker speckles.
The mistle thrush has a distinctive white eye-ring and beak with a yellow base, and orange-brown legs.
They often inhabit woodlands and parks, as well as gardens with mature trees throughout Europe and western Asia.
The mistle thrush is known for its melodious, flute-like song, and its ability to feed on mistletoe berries in the winter.
It is generally a year-round resident bird whose population is considered stable, according to the IUCN Red List.
